Even Orelli was deceived by the imposture. Indeed the great critic of Zurich would probably have left little to be added by his successore had he been aware of the fictitious character of the codices of Bosius. And yet Bosius' own account of the manner in which he gained possession of his vetustissimi codices might have excited suspicion. His Decurtatus (commonly quoted as Y) he obtained from a private soldier who had rescued it in the sack of a monastery, in which it had been de- posited. of his Ormellinus (X) he does not tell his readers the source in his edition published at Limoges, 1580, but he gives the following rather vagus details :— adiutus sum praeterea codice quodam excusso Luqduni qui olim fuerat Petri Grmelli, medici apud nostrates celeberrimi ,· ad cuius libri orae doctus ille vir varias lectiones affinxerat, a se, ut ipse dicebat, diliqentissime et summa fide e vetustissimo et castiyatissimo libro Novioduni demptas.
